class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2460<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/15/02 2:48:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm28.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear Mars Mission</span><hr size=1> Sounds interesting. I want to read that.<br>
<br>
How about a ship that has an onboard Thorium Breeder for transplanting at the Martian base. Thorium is even more common than Uranium so it should be a locatable resource on the Planet. A Breeder would be a safer bet than a regular Uranium reactor at any rate. If there isn't any Thorium then there probably isn't any Uranium so the inhabitants would have to rely on the fuel they took along with them. That fuel could possibly be recycled by the Breeder but I don't know if it could then use that material itself. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1494<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/15/02 11:01:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm28.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear Mars Mission</span><hr size=1> Here is a space.com story titled: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.space.com/scienceastronomy/solarsystem/nuclearmars_000521.html">Will Nuclear Power Put Humans On Mars?</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> from May, 2000.<br>
