Well, an AD design is deliberately adding an extra system to the powerplant.  IE, the particle accelerator is a pure add-on, not needed for making power(if you use the right fuel).  It adds tremendous value in terrestrial applications by making the powerplant directly throttleable, but at the expense of some complexity and mass.  In a super-lightweight design, where mass is a critical piece of the puzzle, leaving off that extra system and relying on traditional controls would result in a lighter plant.<br>
<br>
Atomicrod, of Adams Atomic Engines, argues eloquently for pebble-based &quot;micro-fission&quot; plants.  For very small power installations, and assuming you could show sufficient durability of the fuel pebbles in that usage, then that sort of a super-critical but density controlled reactor could probably be made much lighter than a similar AD system.<br>
